english:
  title: Two Poems Following the Rhymes of Kim Tae-su, the Prefect
  author: Kang Hi-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Chang'an lies distant—how many gates and river crossings stand between?
    Behind closed doors, the long bamboo grove shelters one aging frame.
    Incense burns before old texts as the noon dream crumbles to dust,
    and across the courtyard, sparse rain falls where few visitors come.

    Golden saddle on the prancing horse—each hoof strikes jade sparks,
    while in the imperial city flowers bloom and orioles sing in confusion.
    The spring wind after drunkenness—merely a dream that has passed,
    and I lie at ease on the western bank, white-haired and grown old.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem is structured as two quatrains, each developing themes of retreat from official life and the passage of time.
  - key: ''
    value: Chang'an (long an) refers to the ancient imperial capital, symbolizing the bustling world of power and ambition the poet has left behind.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the first poem's quiet hermitage and the second's vivid memories of court life emphasizes the bittersweet nature of withdrawal.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'white hair' and 'western bank' (often associated with old age and the end of life in Classical Chinese poetry) suggest the poet contemplates mortality.
